******
[2]
Date: Tue 6 Jul 2021
Source: JNews Australia [edited]
https://jnews.com.au/2021/07/06/about-200-people-were-poisoned-off-a-beach-in-algeria-and-authorities-have-opened-an-investigation-politics-international-diversity/


Around 200 people fell ill after [swimming in the ocean] in northwestern Algeria on Sunday [4 Jul 2021] and were admitted to hospital after a possible poisoning from the sea, local and medical officials said.

Three beaches were closed, as was a desalination plant in the area, and prosecutors in the state of [Chlef] opened an investigation into the location of [Tenes].

The governor of [Chlef] told Lakhdar that the victims were suffering from bacterial [?], fever, and red eyes, and all had been discharged from the hospital.

[Chlef's] prevention officer at the Directorate of Health and Population, Nasser El-Din Ben Cartelia, was of the opinion that "victims floating on the central beach of [Tenes] had narrowed [?] the gas, which spread quickly. The wind that blew throughout the afternoon on Sunday [4 Jul 2021]"... [the remainder of the section was not clearly translated so it was removed. - Mod.JH]

Al-Wali said, "We do not rule out any hypothesis, but at present, the possible hypothesis relates to the leakage of a ship carrying animal food into the sea of [Tenes]."

A news website reported that a cargo ship named "Barhoom 2" had sailed from the port of Sete in southern France.

Another hypothesis is that toxic microscopic algae spread in the water, according to Reda Dejeber, a professor in the Faculty of Biological Sciences at the University of Bab Izjuvar in Algiers.

A team of divers was dispatched to search for harmful pollutants, and 36 members of the divers fell ill, including professional divers from the Civil Defense.

An official statement said a delegation from the Ministry of Environment took air and water samples at [Tenes] ports, beaches, valleys near beaches, and facilities that cause pollution.

