******
[3]
Date: Mon 5 Jul 2021
Source: EnTV.dz [edited]
https://www.entv.dz/tenes-beach-victims-of-gas-poisoning-left-hospital/


The victims of gas poisoning, evacuated on Sunday [4 Jul 2021] evening to Ziroud Youcef hospital in Tenes (Chlef province), have all left the health establishment after receiving necessary care, an official at the local Directorate of Health and Population (DHP) said Monday [5 Jul 2021].

"Out of the 193 people admitted to the hospital of Tenes on Sunday [4 Jul 2021] evening, 7 spent the night there and left the hospital on Monday [5 Jul 2021] at 7 a.m. after receiving necessary care," stated the head of prevention at the same department, Dr Nasreddine Benkartalia.

He reported that the people admitted to the hospital of Tenes presented various symptoms such as fever, nausea, vomiting, redness in eyes, and allergy, noting doctors and paramedical staff stood by their bedside until the early morning.

Speaking on the regional radio of Chlef, the wali (governor), Lakhdar [Sadas], confirmed that no victim of the poisoning is currently in the hospital of Tenes, mentioning the setting up of a commission of enquiry in order to know the "ins and outs" of this case.

"Services from various security bodies went to the central beach of Tenes yesterday [4 Jul 2021] evening in order to carry out the usual analyses, necessary in such circumstances, which require high technology," he said.

On the same occasion, the province mayor announced the Ministry of the Environment had sent a specialized commission to analyze the waters of the river located next to the beach.

"No hypothesis will be neglected, but, obviously, the most plausible one (it comes back with insistence) is the one related to the dumping of a boat off Tenes of animals' food," he [stated], mentioning the opening of an investigation on this issue by the prosecutor's office of Chlef.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This poisoning is a little hard to understand, as the earliest report mentions it may have come from a cattle ship. While it is possible the ship offloaded some manure into the water, these articles indicate that the victims all had red eyes, fever, nausea, and vomiting.

If the ship did unload manure, it may have set up a situation for toxic algae to proliferate. Toxic algae in airborne seafoam or spray can cause skin issues, red eyes, and nausea and occasionally vomiting, depending upon the species of algae and its toxin. Fever has been reported in some individuals from toxic algae.

It is not possible to definitively say if the illnesses were caused by a toxic algae bloom, brought on by something perhaps dumped from the ship. Appropriate temperature and conditions can cause algae blooms, and these algal blooms and spray on water surface could indeed cause such reactions.

We await the results of the investigation. - Mod.TG

